"Keep smiling because life is a beautiful thing and there's so much to smile about." -Marilyn Monroe --- Happy Wednesday, friends! I am smiling today because I've survived a year in braces! ğŸ˜It's been quite a journey, and I sure miss eating Sour Patch Kids and Peachy Os, and being able to bite into things like a normal person. But for most of my life, my teeth have been the source of one of my biggest insecurities and fears (because I'm also a wimp when it comes to anything dental related, and avoided the dentist for an embarrassingly long time), so this has been a big step forward for me. Sharing the #love today on #wearestemsquad. This amazing man was my cheerleader on Sunday when I ran the SF @runrocknroll half marathon to raise money for the Parkinson's Disease Foundation. He surprised me with these awesome signs 8 miles into my run just after I crossed the Golden Gate Bridge. The timing couldn't have been more perfect and apparently the signs were effective because I ran the second half of the race faster than the first! . I've really enjoyed reading other #stemsquad posts today about love and how it's essential for getting through grad school, a challenging career or just life in general. I pride myself in being a strong, independent woman, but I also am proud that I can lean on people that I love when I need support or comfort. No matter how stressful life can get, or how many things go wrong even when this was your year to have things go right, remember you have your people who care for you and will help you get back on top. . || I believe the universe always gives back more, no matter what you put into it, always more. I've noticed in my life that because I constantly reach out and actively seek opportunities, I receive a shower of opportunities in return. They may not happen right away, sometimes even years later, but when they do come, they arrive in the form of a big, exciting leap forward. It's important to remember that this phenomenon doesn't work unless you do; you'll get nothing if you do nothing. But if you keep pushing and using a shotgun approach to create any and every route for forward progression that you can think of, you will see that things happen, more than you expect, maybe even more than you deserve. I firmly believe life is supposed to be a positive experience. It's supposed to be great. But you will only get what you create. So make it a good one! ||

Mind the little things. . When we think about saucha, or cleanliness, we might experience a small moment of panic when we realize that we have a mountain of things that need to be cleaned. We have to maintain a certain level of cleanliness in our homes, our work spaces, our bodies, and our minds. The sheer number of tasks necessary to keep everything neat and orderly can be overwhelming. . If, instead of doing massive overhauls or cleaning marathons, we took care of tasks one by one as they arose, I imagine we'd save a lot of time and energy. It's much easier and more rewarding to clean one little mess, than to be faced with a giant mess, or a big pile of little messes. . Mind the little things. Clean up messes as they arise. Wash dishes after each meal so you don't end up with a sink full of dirty dishes at the end of the week. Make healthy food choices regularly, and you likely won't feel the need to do month-long cleanse. Take the clearest expression of a yoga posture that you can, even if that means doing a level one or two of the pose. . Mind the little things.

At the wonderful #manresa in #sanfrancisco #losgatos  chef @davidkinch is cooking up a storm, I went for dinner after getting in the same day from London so the mind & body was on serious jet lag. The head was thinking it was breakfast time but the tummy knew otherwise. Some great inventive dishes coming out of his kitchen. A red pepper pate de fruit, black olive Madeline. A breakfast granola crisp, soft leek with marinated scallop & roe, a beautiful soft cooked egg with parsley & a spiced maple bacon syrup. Caviar with smoked sour cream & baby sorrel leaves,  beautiful crab meat with a yuzo pannacotta was outstanding. Spotted prawn with asparagus cooked in its own juice & butter with a herb crumb. A lovely salad of wild & garden herbs & flowers. Abalone & sea urchin with soba noodles with a brown rice stock was also delicious .... more to follow

The No Place Project: San Francisco, California 1877 - 2 of 4 - Intersection Where the Anti-Chinese Rioters Were Stopped  At least 500 of the men at The Sandlot marched toward Chinatown. The San Francisco police were able to get a large contingent of officers out in front of the crowd, and just outside of Chinatown, at the corner of California and Dupont Streets, the police formed a double line to block the way. The mob charged the police line, but the police pushed them back. The size and force of the police line successfully halted the attack, and within an hour the marchers began to disperse.  Another mob from The Sandlot tried to go around to the north end of Chinatown, but they found another police line waiting for them there. As we go about dropping random pins on conventional maps into this city we call home and explore uncharted corners bearing our tourist hats time and again, we can't help but gape at the wonder that is San Francisco! Full of color, full of culture, full of gastronomic wonders, full of musically driven audiences and artists alike, full of art, full of energy; and full of hustle and bustle! There's a beat to this city that simply refuses to be captured in mere words or two dimensional frames! Free spirits walk by the dozens here, carefree and jovial in their gaits, curious tourists appear like bubbly froth on freshly brewed beer and locals seem to never get over the wholesomeness of this concrete, artsy and strategically located jungle! The original hipster town remains our favorite home ground and we could hardly put into words at how thankful we are for it!! Now that's a corner of the city that I've never seen before! Have you? P.S. They have the most interesting and eclectic collection of vintage-y items in a dainty old thrift store right outside the alley!!! Made our day!!! And I'm glad we made a day out of this micro adventure!! Say what's up weird-camelback-rider-with no shoes on? Climate change is real. It is happening NOW. Carbon pollution is warming our planet and creating extreme droughts, flooding, wildfires and superstorms. Right now we are on track to see global temperatures rise up to 4 degrees by the end of the century. With a shift to clean energy we can still create a sustainable future, but we have to act now! Nature doesn't need people, people need nature. Our food, our water, our health, our jobs-they all rely on the health of the planet's ecosystems. But we are taking more from nature than nature can give. We are weakening the Earth's ability to provide the clean air, fresh water and food we depend on. We are creating a crisis! But we can end this crisis! I have teamed up with Conservation International to raise donations to support their organization by fundraising for the San Francisco Marathon I will be running in July. Conservation International is an amazing organization which works at every level, from remote villages to the offices of presidents and CEOs. Their work is moving entire societies towards a healthier, more sustainable path, so that we don't use up today what we are going to need tomorrow. Conservation International builds upon the foundation of science, field work and are finding global solutions to global problems. They have 3 elements: protecting our natural wealth, fostering effective governance and promoting sustainable production. Their vision is a healthy, prosperous world for the long term benefit of all people and life on Earth. I am proud to support such an inspiring organization! So please stand with me! Together we can make a difference to help save our planet. My fundraising page link is in my bio so please take a moment to donate. Lee Mingwei (American, born 1964) 100 Days with Lily, 1996 Five chromogenic prints . . "Taiwan-born artist Lee Mingwei stages rarely considered rituals of daily life as participatory activities in museums and public spaces, treating them almost as sacred practices. In this way, he encourages audiences to revalue them and the interactions they foster. In 1995 Lee planted a lily in a pot and carried it with him wherever he went for 100 days as the plant sprouted, grew, bloomed and died. A private contemplative activity, his action was also a catalyst for unplanned social exchanges, many inevitably focused on such profound issues as love, worship, loss and mourning. The documentary images from Lee's life with the plant in San Francisco are overprinted with excerpts from the journal he kept durning the project." . #LeeMingwei #100DaysWithLily #1996 #chromogenicprint #chromogenic #barnesfoundation #personofthecrowd #philly #philadelphia #lily #lilies #ritual #activity #sacredpractice #sacred #interaction #100days #sprout #grow #bloom #die #journal #contemplative #socialexchange #love #worship #loss #mourning #SanFrancisco

(1/2) "I wish I had some story about Sleepy to make him a larger than life hero. Instead, Sleepy was just like any other person out there. He was always able to make us laugh and was solid when shit hit the fan. Like all of us soldiers, he was terrified of what could happen, but faced it with bravery and a sense of humor. We all had hard times coming home, some of us were able to pull through others were not. I wish I could have done more to help him pull through, but there was only so much I could do. Now, I did the walk for honor, for Sleepy's honor, and for my own." Eric is an Afghanistan War Veteran who walked in the American Foundation for Suicide Prevention Overnight Walk in San Francisco 2016 raising money for mental health resources and breaking stigma against mental illness for his comrade, who died by suicide post deployment, and himself. -- @afspnational @afsporegon #candidphotography #candid #photojournalism #photojournalist #photojourney  #suicideprevention #afspovernight #nikonphotography #nikon #veteran #ptsd #mentalhealth #mentalhealthawareness #stigma #stigmafree #raiseawareness #portraitphotography #portrait #portlandphotographer #portlandoregonphotographer #pdxphotographer #pnwphotographer #sanfrancisco  #rip #inmemory

I will remember yesterday forever. I walked so extensively that my heels bled. However, I smiled so much and my breath was taken away so often by this city that I didn't even notice the injuries until I took off my shoes later that evening. This is a city where nature was at the forefront, where dogs greeted me at little French restaurants, where jazz musicians filled the air of the streets with their sweet sounds, where everyone was smiling and turn after turn stunning vistas awaited my simple midwestern eyes. I am not naive. I know I could never afford to live there or even venture to dream that I could, but I was without a doubt love-drunk with this city. There is so much that I was unable to see on such a short stay, but I am confident that when I return I will be just as amazed. #sanfrancisco #thecity #sanfran #goldengatebridge #chrissyfield #fillmorestreet #fillmorestairs #corgi #bayarea #sanfranciscobay #sunset #champagnetasteonatapwaterbudget

President Trump has vowed to take away federal funding from cities that refuse to comply with federal immigration laws, and San Franciso stands to lose more than a billion dollars in funding. But the city remains defiant, with the mayor declaring: "We're ready, we have to fight." We used to climb up that hill, which we called snake mountain, with pieces of cardboard and slide down as fast as we could. There used to be a big barn over by the peppercorn tree and my grandpa had a goat named Nanni who lived there. We were forbidden from going into it, but we did it anyway. Nanni wasn't always nice, so we carefully snuck in and ran out before we were head butted. When I turned 15, I learned to drive a stick shift on this land and later my grandpa taught me how to work on tractors...not that much of that sank in, haha. This is where I learned how to set the table, cook by taste, and bake with only the best German chocolate. This is my home. â¤ï¸#home #homeiswheretheheartis

::Motivation Monday:: Striving for perfection may be the most soul crushing endeavor we undertake. Trying to control everything is a dead end as well. Authenticity and the right self acceptance are two huge keys to happiness. The things that keep us from moving forward are anchored in our past. Whoa, right?!? We should figure out what those things are, understand them, and then get rid of them. Fear is the biggest liar that we have and can manifest itself in a plethora of different ways; confusion, unhappiness, control, paranoia, overthinking, anxiousness, apprehension, etc. In fact sometimes because of those anchors that hold us back, fear can make something look like the wrong path when it's the exact one we need. â€¢ I'd like to encourage you to live in the moment while not letting the past affect your present and future. Don't try to control the situations going on in your life and don't try to control what path your life is taking. Since I was a kid, I loved art. I loved drawing and coloring in elementary and had quite the imagination. It followed me  through middle school and high school. I didn't start painting on Canvas until I was 23. I've never sold anything though... I always just did it for fun, I honestly never felt that anything I created would be "good enough" for someone to actually want to purchase. I've always thought there are better people, which is completely true, BUT What I've realized is that there isn't bad art. Every piece you'll see is someone's masterpiece and expression that was birthed from that beautiful heart and creative mind. I have gone YEARS being insecure with what I create. It's super annoying!! So this year I'm going to make art one of the things I'm just going to be confident in, because life is too short to waste it on holding yourself back due to the negative thoughts you feed yourself. These buildings looked well-kept and functional from a distance, but their dilapidation made for an eerie glance at Angel Island. Fort McDowell was built in the late 19th century and, among other purposes, was used as a detention station for Japanese, German, and Italian immigrant residents of Hawaii in WWII. I love being able to explore like this by sailboat - it opens up a whole world of discovery. S A N C T U A R Y . . . Well through a very strange and painful turn events I wound up in San Francisco to be reminded of sanctuary. To re-remember that my body is my home, that there is a wisdom to its longings and messages. I was brought here to literally rest and digest. And I cannot wait to teach about the body of wisdom tomorrow night on The Wild Calling. I dare you to do one thing today that your body deeply desires, to make space to listen to its messages, to begin to build a relationship to trusting it. This is definitely my ongoing work this lifetime. What is "Prana In vs. Prana Out" as referenced below in part 6 of my interview with @amalaprenatal?  Ask yourself these questions: What fuels you? What brings you joy? What gives you energy and life? What is your dharma, your purpose? What feeds you? The answers to these questions make up "Prana In" - that which gives you life.  Now ask yourself: what are the things that drain you, give you stress? What can you let go of? What can you say no to? What no longer serves you? The answers to these questions make up your "Prana Out" - that which takes away from your universal lifeforce. This week, how will you prioritize this balance of Prana In and Prana Out? #maintainbalance  #Repost @amalaprenatal with @repostapp ãƒ»ãƒ»ãƒ» Part 6 of our interview with Shannon Terschluse @findyourprana ------------------------- Q: How has Amalaâ€™s Prenatal Yoga Training affected your teaching? A: Amalaâ€™s training has affected my teaching in so many positive ways! Training brought me back to the very basics of yoga after so many years of focusing on teaching asana and the physicality of the practice. I loved exploring Sankalpa and Vikalpa, the Koshas, and the idea of â€œPrana In vs. Prana Outâ€ â€“ all important ideas and theories that forced me to reflect on my own practice. I loved learning new meditations and feel grateful to be able to use so many of these meditations from training in my own teaching, both to pregnant women and non-pregnant people alike. Amalaâ€™s training allowed me to connect more deeply with my own yoga practice on mind, body, and spirit levels, which in turn, have helped me connect more deeply with students as a teacher.

Seen here from the corner of Pacific Avenue the Sentinel Building, a copper green flatiron style building completed in 1917 appears to stand as tall as the Transamerica Pyramid built in 1972. In fact it is only 8 stories high while the four sided pyramid has 48 floors and was the tallest building in San Francisco a few months ago. The faÃ§ade has a coating of crushed quartz which gives it the light colour. Both buildings have changed ownership in recent years with the Sentinel Building now belonging to film-maker Francis Ford Coppola.

ğŸ“²@everart.io ğŸ™ŒğŸ¾CONGRATS @legacybros  Courtesy @ancestorproject  We are pleased to announce the recent appointment of Daniel Dunson as curator and ambassador of the Ancestor Project @ancestorproject. Dunson is the first African American to join the Osramba team; his goal is to link the project to our brothers and sisters of the diaspora. As head curator, Dunson will be curating exhibitions throughout Africa and the Western world, and will serve as the African American representative for the project. His curatorial debut with The Faux-Reedom Exhibition will take place in June (TBA) at Cape Coast Castle in Cape Coast, Ghana.  Dunson recently graduated from The University of Illinois at Chicago, where he studied art history. He is a 2016 Fulbright Grant recipient and Gilman Scholarship fellow. Dunson is forming a lifelong career in the fields of art history and visual culture. His research as an art historian has been primarily focused on figurative representations within Black Atlantic Art. Dunson has spent the last four years studying in West and North Africa analyzing tethers of the African Diaspora, while unifying them with contemporary and traditional African art. Dunsonâ€™s art criticisms, and editorials have been recently published in magazines in France and England, and he has presented his art historical research at symposiums and conferences in the United States, Morocco, South Africa, and Ghana. Dunson is currently conducting research that positions portraiture aligned with the art of space, place, and memory, and the Middle Passage as he surveys the visual culture of Ghanaian cemeteries and funerary arts. Dunsonâ€™s digital curatorial practice on Instagram (@legacybros) primarily focuses on figurative representations of blackness. Dunson plans to pursue a Ph.D. in art history in 2018.  #everartio #ancestorproject #fauxreedom

Midori and Pablo were really my kind of couple! @Midori.Sour contacted me way back in early January, when I was a newbie to the US and seeking any kind of opportunity to shoot in this place where I knew no-one! I offered a special deal and Midori found me on MeetUp and immediately got in touch! From the moment we first spoke I knew that he had a special kind of vision for her shoot and I loved the locations she described. We met up about a month ago and brainstormed some ideas - this girl has a killer creative vision which I am super inspired by! Fast forward 2 and a half months from our first contact and we finally got to shoot her and Pablo's sun-drenched celebration of their engagement in Lands End, San Francisco. We had waited so long for the weather to be right, because Midori really wanted that backlit feel with the serene & beautiful Californian light... and this was something I was determined to give her. Unfortunately that was easier said than done with the winter we've just had (and has returned with a vengeance today, it seems). But we finally got our day towards the end of March and I'm delighted to be able to publish an image or two from Midori and Pablo's magical shoot. More to follow plus blog post. Congratulations, Midori & Pablo and what an honor it was to get to know you a little!

I would like to bring attention to a Sunset family who is an integral part of this village, giving much of their time and energy to helping to make our village a better place but are themselves struggling with an extreme "life challenge" and could really use our help... Charlie suffers from the genetic disease PKD (Polycystic Kidney Disease) and desperately needs a kidney donated to him. The process of donating a kidney is much easier than one might think and labor laws allow for time off to do so. I feel that somewhere in this village is someone who can help Charlie, a student teacher at AP Gianini who has an adorable little daughter named Alice and an amazing wife named Ashley @aesummers Who is super proactive in our community as the legislative aide to Supervisor Katy Tang. Both Charlie and Ashley grew up in the Outer Sunset... good chances you know them or have crossed paths. They need our help. Please consider donating a kidney or help to get the word out. More information at www.facebook.com/KidneyforCharlie or please feel free to reach out to me as I happy to give you more information and/or introduce you to them. I believe that somewhere in our Sunset village is the benevolent, kind soul who can help them. Please help me to connect Charlie and his beautiful family with a life saving kidney. #sunsetsf #outersunset #sf #sanfrancisco #kidney #kidney #pkd #polycystickidneydisease #community #kidneydonation #sunsetdistrict #sunsetlove

ğŸŒ¿ğŸŒ¿ğŸŒ¿Seven months ago today I was walking around Mission and saw this beautiful place - greenery was bursting with freshness, sundrops were jumping from leaf to leaf... It was not a park, or any outdoor space. Nor it was a greenhouse, or a flower shop... A venue with large windows and lots of plants - I wondered what it was: a cafe, a bar...? I walked inside. It turned out to be a hair salon. I was fascinated - and booked an appointment for the following day. My stylist was Jenny - a friendly petite beauty with long gorgeous red hair. My first #Switchfoot show and VIP was three years ago today.  #FadingWest #RegencyBallroom #SanFrancisco #Stars #LoveAloneIsWorthTheFight #DarkHorses #YourLoveIsASong #CasualJon  Can't wait to catch a few shows #LookingForSummer  They actually came to UC Davis with Relient K in 2007 when i was a freshman living on campus. I didn't manage the courage to try to buy tickets until the discounted student ones had already sold out and i couldn't afford regular price. The night they performed, my dad picked me up to go home for the weekend. I was so sad as we passed by the ARC and saw their buses.  I left work early and took Amtrak and BART to get to San Francisco. I decided to do VIP since it was only $47 and i wanted to be up close for the general admission show. Google maps told me the venue was a mile away so I decided to walk instead of waiting for a bus. It didn't tell me that part of the mile included a mountain climb hahahah.  I didn't even know the guys names at that point. They introduced themselves but i was still all disheveled from the trek so i don't remember what i said to them.  I was already in bed by the time Jon tweeted that he was doing an aftershow and I wouldn't have made it back in time. The same thing nearly happened earlier  this year in Redding but i zipped back to the venue and caught an epic song and a half.

Friday we had appointments in the city. We had a couple of hours to burn, and since we were over in the Sunset, we went to the zoo since I had never been to the SF Zoo before. As a child, all through my young adult years... I have always enjoyed [loved] going to zoos and aquariums. It's a fine line... I love experiencing and learning about animals, but at the same time I also wish they were safe to freely roam in their natural habitat, without fear of being hunted or displaced. Ideally, a holographic zoo would be the best compromise. Granted, if poachers and land cultivation keep endangering the animals... we may not have a choice in that. Many of the animals we saw were on the critically endangered list. And... we just happened to go on the day that Uulu, their Polar Bear passed away, she was 36. I do wish that some of the enclosures were bigger, but it was still a nice zoo. We will, of course, continue to do our part to support and bring awareness to Ocean & Wildlife Conservation... and hopefully have an opportunity to impart that onto the next generation. We did however, have way too much fun playing on all the play structures throughout the zoo. We are definitely overgrown children. #SanFranciscoZoo #SanFrancisco #Zoo #CityZoo #ILoveAnimals #Animals #TheSunset #OliviaAndBear #IHeartMyBear

The VW will reveal their new electric crossover this week at Shanghai Motor Show. . The company released a couple of rendering teasers what is supposed to be a new electric concept crossover. . VW says that the CUV will have autonomous capabilities that will be activated by a simple push VW logo on the steering wheel. In self-driving mode, the steering wheel will be retracted into a car's dashboard. . The concept will have a high capacity battery that gives it a long range on a single charge, similar to gas powered car ranges. . The electric car will feature an all-wheel drive system as well. . The production version of the vehicle will not see the market until at least 2020. . The U.S. travel and tourism industry generated nearly $1.6 trillion in economic output in 2015, supporting 7.6 million U.S. jobs. Travel and tourism exports accounted for 11 percent of all U.S. exports and nearly a third (33 percent) of all U.S. services exports, positioning travel and tourism as the nation's largest services export. One out of every 18 Americans is employed, either directly or indirectly, in a travel or tourism-related industry. In 2015, U.S. travel and tourism output represented 2.6 percent of gross domestic product.  While the majority of activity in the industry is domestic, expenditures by international visitors in the United States totaled $246.2 billion in 2015, yielding a $97.9 billion trade surplus for the year. According to U.S. Department of Commerce projections, international travel to the United States should grow by 3 percent annually through 2021. Ginger Shrimp and Mango Skewers with Paleo Crema  _______________________________________________________  All who know me know that I absolutely LOVE shrimp! ğŸ’œ ğŸ¤ This is why I'm super excited to share a recipe that combines two of my favorite things... shrimp and essential oils!! Put all ingredients for Shrimp marinade into a gallon-sized plastic bag and shake mixture until evenly coated. Leave shrimp to marinate for 1-24 hours. â–  Begin marinating skewers at least one hour in advance of grilling. â–  The crema can be made hours in advance or right before grilling. Put all of the crema ingredients in a medium bowl and whisk to combine. â–  Before you are ready to begin grilling, cut mangoes into chunks and thread the skewers, alternating shrimp and mango. â–  On a hot grill, cook the skewers for 2-3 minutes per side, leaving the skewer alone until you flip it so you can get those gorgeous grill marks. I discovered Rex Ray while living in San Francisco- the fabulous @jonathanadler on Filmore carried his originals and I would visit them often. I remember excitedly finding out that his studio was just a few blocks away from mine in the Mission, I thought about writing him to visit his studio and then had a moment of shyness ğŸ™ˆ and never did. I wish I would have because he passed away in 2015 after quietly battling lymphoma. His work lives on and I am hugely inspired ever time I see it. He is one of my mentors too in the dual place he kept in both the fine art/museum world and the licensing/design world- he created album covers, scarves, rugs, even car wraps for Smart cars! I believe that the more places we can put art, live with art, the better off we are. Thank you Rex Ray!! ğŸ’•

Wowzers! I've been working on a #mindmap for the #matsbootcamp2017 assignment. I got really into this.  It tells my story of living in #sanfrancisco the past 10 years and the #leapsoffaith I've taken along the way. The first leap of faith was moving up here with only an apartment lined up in 2007. Fast forward to 2013, another leap of faith was leaving corporate America to pursue art. I had no idea what that looked like at the time, nor had I sold any of my art before. Fast forward another three years, this summer, I celebrate three years of 100% self-employment making and selling my art in San Francisco. As the mind map suggests, sometimes there's not a clear path outlined, but as long as I follow my joy, I'm confident that I'll find my way. #sanfrancisco #artist #followyourjoy #guidance #lighhouse #sailboats #collage #wallpaper
